{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473987"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11685"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11685"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.22,0.17,0.33,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60586"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4300"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11685"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46011"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18320"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60586"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-month-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with her mother with a two-day history of loose stools and reduced feeding. She had fewer wet nappies yesterday and each was drier than usual. She has also been fussy and irritable. She is normally breastfed and soft foods are being introduced. She has no significant birth history, growth has been appropriate, and developmental milestones are being met. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 175/min (110-180), blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 55/min (20-55), and temperature 37.2\u00b0C (36.5-37.5). Her extremities are warm to touch, her skin is not pale or mottled, central capillary refill time is 4 seconds, the anterior fontanelle is depressed, and the mouth appears dry. Her current weight is 8kg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Encourage more frequent breast feeding","160 mL bolus 0.9% sodium chloride IV stat","50 mL/hr 0.9% sodium chloride with 5% glucose IV over 24 hours","66 mL/hr oral rehydration solution (ORS) via nasogastric tube over 6 hours then 44 mL/hr ORS via nasogastric tube over 18 hours","33 mL/hr oral rehydration solution (ORS) via nasogastric tube over 24 hours"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical picture, this infant is moderately dehydrated with a likely fluid deficit of between 5-9%. \u003Cstrong\u003EOral or nasogastric rehydration\u003C/strong\u003E would be recommended in this situation. Oral rehydration solutions (ORS) such as \u003Cem\u003EPedialyte\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EGastrolyte\u003C/em\u003E are the rehydration fluids of choice in children over one month of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEncouraging more frequent breast feeding\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response. This infant is clinically dehydrated and requires fluid therapy for dehydration. Whilst increased frequency of breastfeeding could help address dehydration, it is very unlikely to be successful in an irritable child who still has ongoing fluid losses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E160 mL bolus of 0.9% sodium chloride IV stat\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response. If urgent fluid resuscitation was required, a 10-20 mL/kg bolus of 0.9% sodium chloride given rapidly would be indicated. However, in the case of moderate dehydration, resuscitation fluids are not required and IV rehydration is not the preferred method.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E50 mL/hr of 0.9% sodium chloride with 5% glucose IV over 24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response. The volume and rate of fluid are appropriate, though should be adjusted for ongoing losses and serum potassium monitored. However, in the case of moderate dehydration, IV rehydration is not the preferred method.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E66 mL/hr of ORS via nasogastric tube over 6 hours then 44 mL/hr of ORS via nasogastric tube over 18 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate response. In moderate dehydration, oral or nasogastric fluid replacement is recommended. In the first 6 hours, the 5% deficit should be replaced. Then the patient would be clinically reassessed, and daily maintenance fluids should be given over the next 18 hours if required. Volume required and delivery rate are determined by admission weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECALCULATIONS\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5% deficit = 8kg (assume all water = 8000ml) x 5% = 400ml\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E400ml / 6 hours = 66ml/hr\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDaily maintenance fluids = 100 x weight (8kg) = 800ml. Give over 18 hours = 44ml/hr\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E(alternate calculation with. 4:2:1 rule: 4x8 = 32ml/hr x 24 hours = 768ml in 24hr / 18hrs = 43ml/hr)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is considered slow nasogastric rehydration. \u003Cstrong\u003ERapid nasogastric rehydration\u003C/strong\u003E could also be appropriate in this situation. It is indicated for moderate dehydration in illnesses such as gastroenteritis to reduce need for prolonged hospital stay and facilitate discharge to home care. Rapid rehydration is not suitable in children less than 6 months old, or if significant comorbidities or abdominal pain are present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E33 mL/hr of ORS via nasogastric tube over 24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response. This is not the correct fluid volume or rate for nasogastric rehydration in a child. In an unwell child, fluid restriction to 2/3 of maintenance fluids should be utilized. For a 5-month-old, 150 mL/kg/day is recommended to meet nutritional and growth requirements, or 100 mL/kg/day for an unwell child which would give approximately 800 mL/day. However, if dehydration is present, the 2/3 maintenance fluids are not typically used.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Enteral (oral or nasogastric) rehydration is preferred for mild and moderate dehydration in children","Rapid nasogastric rehydration is not suitable for children less than six months old"],"references":["The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital, Melbourne, Australia, Clinical Practice Guideline on Dehydration, [Internet, last updated September 2020; cited 11/07/2022], Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Dehydration/","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Clinical Practice Guidelines : Nasogastric Fluids [Internet]. www.rch.org.au. 2021. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Nasogastric_Fluids/","\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46011"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11685"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46011"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-13T07:56:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-13T07:57:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id"